# INSERT

`INSERT` writes values to [user-defined tables](../create-table).

## Conceptual framework

You might want to `INSERT` data into tables when:

- Manually inserting rows into Materialize from a non-streaming data
  source.
- Testing Materialize’s features without setting up a data stream.

## Syntax

<div class="rr-diagram">

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

</div>

<col style="width: 50%" />

<tr>
<th>Field</th>
<th>Use</th>
</tr>
</thead>

<tr>
<td><strong>INSERT INTO</strong> <em>table_name</em></td>
<td>The table to write values to.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><em>alias</em></td>
<td>Only permit references to <em>table_name</em> as
<em>alias</em>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><em>column_name</em>…</td>
<td>Correlates the inserted rows’ columns to <em>table_name</em>’s
columns by ordinal position, i.e. the first column of the row to insert
is correlated to the first named column.<br />
<br />
If some but not all of <em>table_name</em>’s columns are provided, the
unprovided columns receive their type’s default value, or
<code>NULL</code> if no default value was specified.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><em>expr</em>…</td>
<td>The expression or value to be inserted into the column. If a given
column is nullable, a <code>NULL</code> value may be provided.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><em>query</em></td>
<td>A <a href="../select"><code>SELECT</code></a> statements whose
returned rows you want to write to the table.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

## Details

The optional `RETURNING` clause causes `INSERT` to return values based
on each inserted row.

### Known limitations

- `INSERT ... SELECT` can reference [user-created
  tables](../create-table) but not [sources](../create-source) *(or
  views, materialized views, and indexes that depend on sources)*.
- **Low performance.** While processing an `INSERT ... SELECT`
  statement, Materialize cannot process other `INSERT`, `UPDATE`, or
  `DELETE` statements.

## Examples

To insert data into a table, execute an `INSERT` statement where the
`VALUES` clause is followed by a list of tuples. Each tuple in the
`VALUES` clause must have a value for each column in the table. If a
column is nullable, a `NULL` value may be provided.

<div class="highlight">

``` chroma
CREATE TABLE t (a int, b text NOT NULL);

INSERT INTO t VALUES (1, 'a'), (NULL, 'b');

SELECT * FROM t;
 a | b
---+---
   | b
 1 | a
```

</div>

In the above example, the second tuple provides a `NULL` value for
column `a`, which is nullable. `NULL` values may not be inserted into
column `b`, which is not nullable.

You may also insert data using a column specification.

<div class="highlight">

``` chroma
CREATE TABLE t (a int, b text NOT NULL);

INSERT INTO t (b, a) VALUES ('a', 1), ('b', NULL);

SELECT * FROM t;
```

</div>

```
 a | b
---+---
   | b
 1 | a
```

You can also insert the values returned from `SELECT` statements:

<div class="highlight">

``` chroma
CREATE TABLE s (a text);

INSERT INTO s VALUES ('c');

INSERT INTO t (b) SELECT * FROM s;

SELECT * FROM t;
```

</div>

```
 a | b
---+---
   | b
   | c
 1 | a
```

## Privileges

The privileges required to execute this statement are:

- `USAGE` privileges on the schemas that all relations and types in the
  query are contained in.
- `INSERT` privileges on `table_name`.
- `SELECT` privileges on all relations in the query.
  - NOTE: if any item is a view, then the view owner must also have the
    necessary privileges to execute the view definition. Even if the
    view owner is a *superuser*, they still must explicitly be granted
    the necessary privileges.
- `USAGE` privileges on all types used in the query.
- `USAGE` privileges on the active cluster.
